[Avian chlamydiosis (AC) is a zoonotic bacterial infection caused by
_Chlamydophila psittaci_, formerly known as _Chlamydia psittaci_ . In
humans, it can cause Psittacosis, also known as Parrot fever and
Ornithosis, which may lead to severe pneumonia and other serious health
problems. Infected birds -- usually cockatiels, parakeets, parrots, and
macaws -- shed the bacteria through feces and nasal discharges, and humans
become infected from exposure to these materials.
Updated information about psittacosis and AC can be found in the website of
the American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA)
<http://www.avma.org/pubhlth/psittacosis.asp>.
The document -- "Compendium of Measures To Control _Chlamydophila psittaci_
(formerly _Chlamydia psittaci_) Infection Among Humans (Psittacosis) and
Pet Birds, 2003" -- has been issued by the National Association of State
Public Health Veterinarians (NASPHV). It includes recommendations on
standardized procedures for controlling AC in birds, a vital step to
protecting human health. - Mod.AS]
